The mite fauna of FJL is extremely incomplete and fragmentary, as most families (83%) are represented by one genus and most genera (77%) include only one species. This low diversity of genera within families and of species within genera has been observed also in other regions of the Arctic polar deserts (

with additions; 

). More

to the south, in the tundra and taiga zones, the percentage of “monospecific” genera within free-living mite fauna usually fail to exceed 60% among mites in general (
) or within Mesostigmata alone (
;
), or Oribatida alone (
;
;
;
). Taxonomical fragmentation seems to be

a typical regular characteristic of polar desert biota in general (

; 

). So, this pattern is also known from other groups of animals in the FJL, such

as Nematoda, Collembola, and even vertebrates (
Figure 4
).

Very interestingly, the proportion of specialized arctic species among the relatively well known higher taxa, i.e. Mesostigmata (92.3%) and Oribatida (10.0%), appears to vary strongly ( Figure 10 ). The percentage of true arctic and arctic-montane species within Mesostigmata throughout the Arctic is much greater than that of Oribatida (
;
; Makarova 2013, 2015; Makarova et al. 2019;
). This finding may be related to differences in the geological age and evolution rate of these taxa (
). Fossil oribatid mites date back to the Devonian (Norton et al.

1988; 

), while the rate of their morphogenesis is considered to have been unprecedentedly low (

; 

). On the contrary, the earliest record of a member of 
Mesostigmata
dates back to the Cretaceous (

). Molecular investigations designate the Dermanyssina s. l. (the main body of 
Mesostigmata
)

to outgroups in comparison with all other chelicerates (

). Moreover, 
Mesostigmata
generally also have significantly faster rates of nucleotide substitution than do other parasitiform mites, this possibly being related to their higher metabolic rates and shorter life-cycles (

).

Most of the mite assemblages studied are multispecies (20–34 species) and polydominant ( Table 3 ). The total mite abundance in the FJL grounds commonly varies between 120–2,340 ind./dm 2 , locally reaching 3,800 ind./dm
2 in
well-drained tundra-like lush communities with forbs and dwarf willows on the south-faced slope of Tikhaya Bay ( Table 3 ). Almost the same variations have been pointed out for the acarocenoses in the polar deserts of the Severnaya Zemlya Archipelago (40–2,380 ind./dm 2 ;
). These baseline values strongly resemble those recorded in previous works in the tundra zone, but they are significantly lower in comparison with data obtained from taiga zone ( 2,400 –6,200 ind./dm 2 ; references in
).

We have no material from the flat coastal or inland landscapes of FJL (plains and low plateaus), where mite communities are scarce and uniform (Bulavitsev and Babenko, 1983;
). The slope habitats studied in the present paper are populated by species rich and various mite assemblages ( Table 3 , Figure 5 ), even though the sampling sites within both of our transects were contiguous, and the mass species were often numerous in several biotopes ( Table 3 ). Different approaches and methods have been used in ecological investigations of the arctic mites (
;
; McLean et al. 1978; Thomas and McLean 1988;
;
) rendering difficult the comparison of the results. Most of these investigations only deal with Oribatida and/or Mesostigmata data, or with only mass species from different mite suborders. Meanwhile, we can conclude that on FJL, as everywhere in the High Arctic, mite communities are differentiated depending on local environmental conditions. In comparison with Svalbard acarocenoses (
;
;
), the biotopic diversity of mesostigmatic mites on FJL is of the same order of magnitude (2-8 vs. 1-10 species on Svalbard ) while the local species richness of Oribatida

